<br>
First, don't, repeat Don't, work on Tailoring and Weaponsmithing as you run up your Armorcrafting skill.  Wait until your secondary skills lag behind your primary skill by at least 15 points then start working on the lowest level of tailoring and/or weaponsmithing you can, using the cheapest materials available.  I just ran up to 340 in Armorcrafting, but my metal skill was lagging behind at 320.  To advance the skill using metalworking would have cost several gold because I'd have had to use steel or alloy bars.  Instead I made bronze daggers and swords with my 40 Weaponsmithing skill and it popped my leatherworking and metalworking right up to 340 at a cost of a few silvers.  Same with using Tailoring to run clothworking and leatherworking up.<br>
<br>
You might say that you need Tailoring to make the cloth components of plate and scaled armor, but I found that you can't run Tailoring up high enough to make most of the things you need because it always lags behind Armorcrafting at least 50-75 points due to the skill cap.  You save more money by keeping it low to advance clothworking and buying cloth components than by making the random piece that you have enough skill for.<br>
<br>
Any thoughts on this or any other hints?  Please pass them on.<br>
<br>
Hawk, the sweaty cleric. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#6B8E23><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uapo44.showPublicProfile?language=EN>apo44</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(11/19/01 11:28:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=744.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tips for Saving Money on Armorcrafting (and other skills</span><hr size=1> A helpfull hint, I an now a 614 tailor 1 point per 1.5 hour now :P. After you hit 500 find and team up with a tailor 20 points ahead of your skill. 1/2 his order would be grey the other half will give him skill points. The reason not to team up with a tailor at you skill is that 1/2 the orders will give him skill the other 1/2 he will not be able to make. So you will have to buy from a merchant and this will kill your profit(you might even lose money). Also PC tailors should change 20-30% markup(MK). Most charge 30%(MK) once you hit material that they have to leave camelot to get. NEVER pay more than 30%(MK). Also if you need a tailor and can't find one that will make stuff for you contact me. I have no problem making greys for guildies, I already do for regulars(who also give me skill gain iteams). The guild rate is free for camelot sold iteam if you bring me the material and 20%(MK) for items I have to travel for. I really wanted to charge cost but that will not be possible becuse I lose huge amouts on crit fail that at 20%, in the long run I am making a small profit. That profit is then used to power skill fletching to 500 so that I can make two parts of siege equipment. AC should make great money after level 500+, tailors make money from 500-575, after that expect your net value(NV) in gold and material to go up much much slower. I started with 250g(NV) at 575 and still have near the same (NV)  at 614, but I have been powerskill fletching and buying neat armour for about 30g. I hope this helps.<br>
<br>
Nimitz<br>
<br>
Also arrows are a cheap way to power skill metalworking, that what I make when my skill fall behind. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uapo44.showPublicProfile?language=EN>apo44</A> at: 11/19/01 11:31:00 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uboldwini.showPublicProfile?language=EN>boldwini</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(11/19/01 2:51:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=744.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Cool</span><hr size=1> I have been using other crafts to get secondary skills up when they start lagging.  As of this morning I'm at 283 ArmorCrafting(I only get to work on it when Kalaria isn't in game...I.E.. click button, take a shower, click button, lather up face, click button, stroke of the razor, click button, etc... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  <br>
